metadata.name: Antilepton Factory #5
metadata.description:
A quasi-simulation exploring variations of the antimatter content of a primitive universe,
1 048 576 particles are subjected to the fluctuations of a digital scalar force field.

Each one of the 60 frames per second is a unique generative composition.

(Click â€˜openâ€™ to see fullscreen, use wheel/pinch to zoom micro/macro )

-----
* Mint preview *

Minter will get a loopless determinist animation, and a 4320x4320 PNG bitmap.
The "cover" iteration featured here by default uses a 10seconds animation cycle, but new mints will have random animation mode cycles lasting between 1 and 60 seconds. 
To enable the "regular perturbation" mode (10s cycles) please see below "URL modifiers".

-----
* Technics *

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 â†’ 7680x4320) at 60FPS for infinite duration as the animation scales and creates never-before-seen patterns.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL
- Unique generative and determinist animation (animation is seeded by the fxhash mint hash)
- Unlimited duration (no loop) / 6 animations
- 1 second to 1 minute internal algorithm variations

-----
* Controls *

Wheel/pinch : zoom in/out to observe the phenomenon on different scales
Right click + drag : move the observation area
Key "Space" : take a PNG capture of the current view frame (same ratio as window, max 1920x1080)

-----
* URL modifiers *

"&scalartemperature=1400" 
displays the animation with another color.
Colors are expressed in terms of blackbody radiation at a given temperature. Here it will be 1400 Kelvin degrees (~1120Â°C / 2060Â°F) corresponding to a lightly hotter than red particles. 
Values accepted in the range 800K to 1 000 000K.

"&perturbation=regular"
allows a regular cycle of animations, each animation mode will be active for 10 seconds

-----
@HAL09999 â€“ November 2022

metadata.name: fx(mash) #143
metadata.description:
fx(mash) is my humble contribution to celebrating #fxhashturnsone

This series is based on a simple algorithm - lines of a random length are drawn on a square grid until the grid is full.

I have added a variety of features based on some of my favorite fxhash projects and a few special guests.

This collection is intentionally diverse and disorderly, that's a nice way of saying I only had a short period of time following the release of Acequia. As a result, some of the outputs might be weird, messy, or even bordering on broken (if you get one of the latter please let me know and I'll reimburse you).

Despite being a bit rough around the edges, I hope fx(mash) reflects some measure of my love for the fxhash community. If you're feeling kind, then perhaps it even harks back to the experimental early days :)

The last year has been an incredible journey, thank you for letting me be a part of our story so far.

Controls (in live view):

- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [g] to toggle grain
- Press [h] for a high-res output

Beta Controls (in live view, definitely not fully tested):

- Press [p] to start/pause animation
- Press [i] to slow down animation
- Press [o] to speed up animation

All primary sales go to Savepakistan.


Acknowledgements:

fx(mash) uses Gorilla Sun's grain implementation, a big thanks to him and meezwhite for a great article that is well worth supporting https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

metadata.name: Knockout #116
metadata.description:
An exploration of screen printing techniques and how these effects can be achieved in generative work. The halftone effect works by placing very small dots next to each other to give the illusion of new shades and hues. Each Knockout samples three colors for the main composition and runs small sections of the canvas back through the machine after shuffling the base palette. The secondary passes vary in size, creating interesting emergent patterns on the overlap.

Press 's' in live view to save a .png

Built and tested with Chrome on Apple silicon. Some outputs may take up to 20s on slower machines.

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: d/e/m/boss invaders #22
metadata.description:
Invaders is an algorithm that builds rows of rectangles and plays with repetition, colors and depth order.
Outputs reminds me space invaders, but some looks like motherboard circuits, temples, or just a overhead map from a hotel room emergency exit

Please be patient, it takes a while to render (25-45 secs) and draws around 6M circles during 4 steps.

Responsive, zoom out browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas

Invaders is part of a series playing with textures creating emboss/deboss effect.

metadata.name: Life has no scores #124
metadata.description:
We cannot compose life, at best we hum along to the melodies that life has been played in front of us. Looking back at the scores of our lives, the notations are never neatly noted, but fully felt.  Rewinding the songs of life are our memories, whether sad, happy, angry, or melancholy. It is not clear whether I am dreaming or awake, but our songs all do end. 

In this final drop (for ?), I have reused the first ever class calligraphy(){} I have written from my genesis drop â€œNothing comes from nothingâ€. As time passes, 10 drops later, across almost to the year, I am grateful for the progress I have made, as an artist, and more importantly as a human. After all, what is behind the code of generative art is a human being. 

Scores of music, scrolls of calligraphy, calendar or diary, notating life, time passes, and changes are inevitable. Sometimes we sing louder in laughter and joy, sometimes we scribble in uneasiness, sometimes we just get lost in neon lights. Life goes on. You and me, all the same and yet different.  

There are too many friend artists, friend collectors, fxhash team members, to thank for helping me through this journey. I would like to pay homage to Rudxane in this work, who has taken me under his wings, mentoring and encouraging me in art as well as showing me some degen stuff on the side:-). This homage is not copy-minting, or copying of styles, which I do not have the coding skills to do so even if I wanted to. But it is the influence of taste in many works of Rudxane. In a vague but agreeable taste, I present to you Life has no scores. 

What I was taught was disrupted, and grid studies left unfinished, and oh do we have a BINGO?

Tested on Chrome. Other browsers may render different or not at all (firefox)

Press â€˜2â€™ to save png.

metadata.name: Intimate #31
metadata.description:
Intimacy is a beguiling thing,
Elusive and hard to define.
It is the close and personal bond
Between two hearts intertwined.

It has its shadows,
Distortions lead to pain.
Codependency and lack of boundaries,
Possessiveness and control, all the same.

Navigating the delicate balance of intimacy
Is a philosophical pursuit,
Requiring self-awareness and consideration
To nurture healthy, fulfilling roots.

For beneath the surface of every connection,
Lies a layer of memory and history,
Hiding, waiting, to be uncovered
And reveal the true depth of intimacy.

Intimate is a generative audiovisual project that creates audio and visual elements in real time. It is an experimental project in collaboration with KEF and Parameta on fxhash that minters will meet the artist in person and live-mint together in the KEF Music Gallery designed to showcase high-fidelity sound. This immersive experience allows participants to explore the concept of intimacy and its relationship to the artist and collectors.

Click on the canvas to start generative audiovisual.

This work uses p5js, webpd, and glfx.

metadata.name: Forgive Your Sins #38
metadata.description:
This is a colorful remix for #genuary32nd of my late #genuary23 work done on 31st of January!
This is my tribute to Yayoi Kusama (#genuary25) with viscous dots of digital ink thrown in digital liquid and then shaken by digital sine waves (#genuary15) inspired by marbling techniques.

This is the 2nd iteration of my Wasm/Rust fluid simulation engine after "Viscous Circles" collection. Check it on FxHash if you want to know more about the engine behind this generator.

Controls

You can stop at any step if you like the state at this instant, you can restart it, de/increase resolution (default is 4096x4096 to have sharp image, up to 16K x 16K) and snapshot at any resolution.

- H: hide/show help.
- Space - pause/start animation.
- R - restart animation.
- I - hide/show res/fps panel.
- A-Q/D - down/up full resolution
- S - take full resolution snapshot

Now, forgive your sins!

Forgive Your Sins @naibdian 2023 Project made using Opensource WebGL, WASM/Rust/JS libs
#genuary32nd #genuary23 #genuary15 #genuary25

metadata.name: WTBS.TXT #328
metadata.description:
*WTBS.TXT*Â is the first collaboration between Thomas Noya and the Waiting To Be Signed podcast crew. Using the first year of episodes as training data, Thomas trained a GPT-2 model to generate text strings from seed words, phrases, or at random; over 3000 strings were curated from the model over several months. The strings are then randomly selected from the curated set and displayed in various fonts and patterns, evoking a retro-PC style inspired by 90s net.art.

An advantage of using so little data to train a model (yes, a year of content is nothing in AI terms) is that it allows the model to run wild and create funny and fantastical diversions. We used an AI service to transcribe the episodes, which introduced many spelling variations around fx(hash)-specific terms and artist names. All of this adds up to something that we are collectively excited to share with you.

From WTBS: A year went by fast... so fast that we fully missed doing anything to celebrate. Please think of this token as a belated celebration of the first year of Waiting To Be Signed. This project could not be possible without the hours of content we produce each week. If you have enjoyed the show, we hope you will enjoy this as well. Please collect to support the continued creation of WTBS. Collect because you are a fan (of Thomas, us or both). Collect because it is a really cool project. Huge thanks to Thomas for volunteering his time to work with us on this, and thank you to everyone who listened and supported us as we move into our second year of the show.


Controls:

metadata.name: Cascading #56
metadata.description:
Having a flowing and cascading composition is the style that I am referring to in this work. I will convey movement and fluidity in each piece by using angles, lines, and overlapping colors. I want to evoke a feeling of energy and dynamism with this method, so that the elements in the work are in constant motion. A cascading can also be used to convey feelings or ideas, as its flowing nature symbolizes change, growth or transformation.
cascading is a captivating visual style that draws the viewer's eye through a dynamic and fascinating journey through the work.

Made by p5.js
